But before that, I have a question for you.

24
00:01:22,080 --> 00:01:26,800
The earliest coffee to arrive in Britain took its name from the port in Yemen.

25
00:01:26,800 --> 00:01:30,800
It was shipped from, so what was it called?

26
00:01:30,800 --> 00:01:37,520
Was it A, Kapuchino, B, Mocka or C, Latte?

27
00:01:37,520 --> 00:01:39,760
I'll say B, Mocka.

28
00:01:39,760 --> 00:01:42,880
Okay, I'll reveal the answer later in the programme.

29
00:01:42,880 --> 00:01:49,760
Britain's love affair with coffee started with the opening of London's first coffee shop in 1652.

30
00:01:49,840 --> 00:01:51,200
People loved the effect.

31
00:01:51,200 --> 00:01:53,840
Coffee made them more talkative and brighter.

32
00:01:53,840 --> 00:01:58,000
It kept them awake for longer, and the drink became more and more popular.

33
00:01:58,000 --> 00:02:03,120
Within a decade, over 18 new coffee shops had opened in the city of London alone.

34
00:02:03,120 --> 00:02:08,800
By the 1800s, though, tea had replaced coffee as the most fashionable drink,

35
00:02:08,800 --> 00:02:11,840
partly because it was drunk by Queen Victoria.

36
00:02:12,319 --> 00:02:17,040
Listen as Judith Hawley, an expert on 18th century literature,

