going to the pub for lunch.

43
00:02:41,039 --> 00:02:42,000
So it moved.

44
00:02:42,000 --> 00:02:46,399
It declined seriously and has never fully recovered, even in the current coffee boom.

45
00:02:47,919 --> 00:02:53,199
In the 17th century, there was a coffee boom, an increase in its popularity.

46
00:02:53,199 --> 00:02:59,039
One of the reasons was that coffee perks you up, gives you more energy and makes you more active.

47
00:02:59,039 --> 00:03:03,199
Drinking coffee was also supported by a social group called

48
00:03:03,199 --> 00:03:07,599
the Temperance Movement, who campaigned to make alcohol illegal.

49
00:03:08,159 --> 00:03:14,399
They used coffee to wean men off alcohol, make them gradually stop using something

50
00:03:14,399 --> 00:03:16,159
they had become addicted to.

51
00:03:16,159 --> 00:03:20,079
Coffee changed British society and continues to do so today.

52
00:03:20,079 --> 00:03:26,639
Here's Professor Judith Hawley again, talking to BBC Radio 4s in our time about the situation today.

53
00:03:27,439 --> 00:03:30,879
I think if we look at the way coffee consumption is going today,

54
00:03:30,879 --> 00:03:34,639
it seems to me to set out two quite radical alternatives.

55
00:03:34,639 --> 00:03:40,879
For the world one is the world of corporate coffee, the coffee change existing on a low wage

56
00:03:40,879 --> 00:03:41,599
economy.

57
00:03:41,599 --> 00:03:45,199
So you have that kind of mass coffee market on the one hand.

58
00:03:45,199 --> 00:03:50,319
On the other hand, you have these micro lotter states, fair trade coffee,

59
00:03:50,319 --> 00:03:56,239
the sort of hipster coffee which is as varied and as interesting as fine wines,

60
00:03:56,239 --> 00:03:58,159
and is made in an artisan way.

61
00:03:59,119 --> 00:04:03,919
Many customers today are turning away from large coffee chains like Starbucks

62
00:04:03,919 --> 00:04:07,759
in search of a more responsibly sourced cup of coffee.

63
00:04:07,759 --> 00:04:14,319
One example of this is fair trade, an ethical standard scheme which guarantees a fair price for

64
00:04:14,319 --> 00:04:18,639
coffee producers in South America, Africa and Asia.

65
00:04:18,639 --> 00:04:22,319
Another recent development is the use of micro lots.

66
00:04:22,319 --> 00:04:28,319
Small plots of land which grow specialised coffee beans prized for their high quality and unique

67
00:04:28,319 --> 00:04:35,199
flavour. Fair trade and micro lot coffee are parts of a shift in focus towards quality artisanal

68
00:04:35,199 --> 00:04:41,199
coffee, coffee made by hand in the traditional way by skilled growers.

69
00:04:41,199 --> 00:04:46,079
It's artisanal coffee that's often sold in smaller, independent coffee shops

70
00:04:46,079 --> 00:04:48,399
preferred by trendy hipsters.

71
00:04:48,399 --> 00:04:53,439
So coffee in Britain has come a long way from the days it travelled for months by sea,

72
