Ah, I asked Neil which city gave its name to the first coffee to arrive in Britain in the

74
00:05:06,079 --> 00:05:07,279
1600s.

75
00:05:07,279 --> 00:05:10,719
I guess it was B. Mocha, which happens to be my favourite drink.

76
00:05:11,279 --> 00:05:14,879
Well, you guessed right because that was the correct answer.

77
00:05:14,879 --> 00:05:17,039
You certainly know your coffee, Neil.

78
00:05:17,039 --> 00:05:22,079
Right, let's recap the vocabulary we've used in this programme on the history of coffee,

79
00:05:22,079 --> 00:05:26,399
a drink which can perk you up, give you more energy and make you feel awake.

80
00:05:26,399 --> 00:05:32,159
Many people drink coffee for the caffeine hit, the way caffeine, which is contained in coffee,

81
00:05:32,159 --> 00:05:34,319
stimulates your body and mind.

82
00:05:34,319 --> 00:05:39,519
The effect can be so strong you might have to wean yourself off it,

83
00:05:39,519 --> 00:05:42,560
gradually stop using something which is bad for you.

84
00:05:42,560 --> 00:05:47,759
Fair trade coffee refers to a scheme which ensures that coffee farmers receive a fair price

85
00:05:47,759 --> 00:05:53,919
for growing their product, while a micro lot is a small plot of land specialising in coffee beans

86
00:05:53,919 --> 00:05:57,039
of the very high quality or unique flavour.

87
00:05:57,039 --> 00:06:03,759
Finally, artisanal describes something made by artisans, skilled workers who make things by hand

88
00:06:03,759 --> 00:06:05,039
in the traditional way.

89
00:06:05,760 --> 00:06:07,680
Once again, our six minute to wrap.

90
